      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You are absolutely thinking about it correctly! If the salvage value increases to 10,000, the yearly depreciation amount would indeed get smaller.\n\nHere is the math: (50,000 - 10,000) / 5 = 8,000 per year. Since the company plans to keep more of the machine's value at the end, the \"loss\" of value each year is reduced.\n\nThis makes sense because the straight-line method spreads the total depreciable cost evenly. By raising the salvage value, you are essentially saying the machine will still be worth more when it's time to sell it, so you don't depreciate as much of the original cost over its life. It's a common trick in accounting problems to test if you understand that salvage value acts like a floor for the asset's value.\n\nJust remember, in real-world scenarios, estimating a salvage value accurately is often the hardest part for accountants, as it requires a lot of foresight. But for your exam, just plug the new number into the formula and the result will be smaller! Good luck with your studying!",
