      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You are absolutely right, and there is a whole family of methods called \"accelerated depreciation\" that handles exactly that scenario where assets lose value quickly at the start. The most common one is the **Double-Declining Balance** method, which uses twice the straight-line rate.\n\nFor your specific machine, you would calculate the rate as 2 divided by 5 years (which is 40%), and then apply that 40% to the book value at the *beginning* of each year. This means in Year 1, you'd depreciate 40% of the full 50,000 cost, but in later years, the amount gets smaller as the book value drops, until it hits your salvage value floor.\n\nIt's a bit more complex than the straight-line method because the calculation changes every year based on the remaining value, but it perfectly mimics how things like heavy machinery or computers actually wear out. If you get stuck on the math for this one, just remember that you stop depreciating once the book value equals your salvage value of 5,000. You can't depreciate *below* that 5,000 floor, even if the math",
